[30;1m321 | [0m[35mAs an example, take a typical system containing a number of user passwords,[0m
[30;1m322 | [0m[35mall stored using :class:`~passlib.hash.sha256_crypt`.[0m

[30;1m252 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m253 | [0m[35mAll of the basic methods of this object will behave normally, but after[0m
[30;1m254 | [0m[35man application has verified the user entered the correct password, it can[0m
[30;1m255 | [0m[35mcheck to see if the hash has been deprecated using the[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m215[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m

   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m213 | [0m[35m    >>> # or it can be loaded from a local file:[0m
[30;1m214 | [0m[35m    >>> myctx3 = CryptContext.from_path("/some/path/on/local/system")[0m
[30;1m215 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m216 | [0m[35mThis allows applications to completely extract their password hashing[0m
[30;1m217 | [0m[35mpolicies from the code, and into a configuration file with other security settings.[0m

[30;1m50 | [0m[35mBasic Usage[0m
[30;1m51 | [0m[35m===========[0m
[30;1m52 | [0m[35mAt its base, the :class:`!CryptContext` class is just a collection of[0m
[30;1m53 | [0m[35m:class:`~passlib.ifc.PasswordHash` objects, imported by name[0m
[30;1m54 | [0m[35mfrom the :mod:`passlib.hash` module. The following snippet creates[0m
[30;1m55 | [0m[35ma new context object which supports three hash algorithms[0m
[30;1m56 | [0m[35m(:doc:`sha256_crypt </lib/passlib.hash.sha256_crypt>`,[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m226[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/narr/context-tutorial.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m18 | [0m[35m    * identifying the algorithm used by a hash, and then verify a password.[0m
[30;1m19 | [0m[35m    * configure the default algorithm, load in support for new algorithms,[0m
[30;1m20 | [0m[35m      deprecate old ones, set defaults for time-cost parameters, etc.[0m
[30;1m21 | [0m[35m    * migrate hashes / re-hash passwords when an algorithm has been deprecated.[0m
[30;1m22 | [0m[35m    * load said configuration from a sysadmin configurable file.[0m
[30;1m23 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m24 | [0m[35mThe following sections contain a walkthrough of this class, starting[0m

[30;1m13 | [0m[35mThe :mod:`passlib.context` module contains one main class: :class:`!passlib.context.CryptContext`.[0m

[30;1m15 | [0m[35mcoding patterns which occur in applications that need to handle multiple[0m

[30;1m149 | [0m[35mThe digest portion is generated by passing the ``utf-8`` encoded password,[0m
[30;1m150 | [0m[35mthe ``ascii``-encoded salt string, and the number of rounds into[0m
[30;1m151 | [0m[35mPBKDF2 using the HMAC-SHA256 prf; and generated a 32 byte checksum,[0m

[30;1m237 | [0m[35mFormat[0m
[30;1m238 | [0m[35m------[0m
[30;1m239 | [0m[35mAn example :class:`!django_des_crypt` hash (of ``password``) is[0m
[30;1m240 | [0m[35m``crypt$cd1a4$cdlRbNJGImptk``; the general format is the same[0m
[30;1m241 | [0m[35mas the salted hashes: :samp:`{ident}${salt}${checksum}`, where:[0m
[30;1m242 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m233[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m

   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m226 | [0m[35m  rainbow tables.[0m
[30;1m227 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m228 | [0m[35m* They digest the encoded hexadecimal salt, not the raw bytes,[0m
[30;1m229 | [0m[35m  increasing the odds that a particular salt+password string[0m
[30;1m230 | [0m[35m  will be present in a pre-computed tables of ascii digests.[0m
[30;1m231 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m232 | [0m[35mDes Crypt Wrapper[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m234[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m

[30;1m212 | [0m[35mThe checksum is generated by concatenating the salt digits followed[0m
[30;1m213 | [0m[35mby the password, and hashing them using the specified digest (MD5 or SHA-1).[0m
[30;1m214 | [0m[35mThe digest is then encoded to hexadecimal.[0m
[30;1m215 | [0m[35mIf the password is unicode, it is converted to ``utf-8`` first.[0m
[30;1m216 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m235[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.django_std.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m210 | [0m[35m* :samp:`{checksum}` is lowercase hexadecimal encoding of the checksum.[0m
[30;1m211 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m212 | [0m[35mThe checksum is generated by concatenating the salt digits followed[0m
[30;1m213 | [0m[35mby the password, and hashing them using the specified digest (MD5 or SHA-1).[0m
[30;1m214 | [0m[35mThe digest is then encoded to hexadecimal.[0m
[30;1m215 | [0m[35mIf the password is unicode, it is converted to ``utf-8`` first.[0m
[30;1m216 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m243[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.django_std.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m160 | [0m[35m    All of the following hashes are very susceptible to brute-force attacks;[0m
[30;1m161 | [0m[35m    since they are simple single-round salted digests.[0m
[30;1m162 | [0m[35m    They should not be used for any purpose[0m
[30;1m163 | [0m[35m    besides manipulating existing Django password hashes.[0m
[30;1m164 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m165 | [0m[35mDjango 1.0 supports some basic salted digests, as well as some[0m
[30;1m166 | [0m[35mlegacy hashes:[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m244[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.django_std.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m146 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m147 | [0m[35m* :samp:`{checksum}` is the base64 encoding the PBKDF2 digest.[0m
[30;1m148 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m149 | [0m[35mThe digest portion is generated by passing the ``utf-8`` encoded password,[0m
[30;1m150 | [0m[35mthe ``ascii``-encoded salt string, and the number of rounds into[0m
[30;1m151 | [0m[35mPBKDF2 using the HMAC-SHA256 prf; and generated a 32 byte checksum,[0m
[30;1m152 | [0m[35mwhich is then encoding using base64.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m245[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m

[30;1m108 | [0m[35mSecurity Issues[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m272[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m

[30;1m101 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m103 | [0m[35mThe password is encoded into UTF-8 if not already encoded, and handed off to the Argon2 function.[0m
[30;1m104 | [0m[35mA specified number of bytes (16 byte default in passlib) returned result are encoded as the checksum[0m
[30;1m105 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m58 | [0m[35mIt's compatible with the :ref:`PHC Format <phc-format>` and :ref:`modular-crypt-format`,[0m
[30;1m59 | [0m[35mand uses ``$argon2i$``, ``$argon2d$``, or ``$argon2id$`` as the identifying prefixes [0m
[30;1m60 | [0m[35mfor all its strings. An example hash (of ``password``) is:[0m
[30;1m61 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m62 | [0m[35m  ``$argon2i$v=19$m=512,t=3,p=2$c29tZXNhbHQ$SqlVijFGiPG+935vDSGEsA``[0m
[30;1m63 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m32 | [0m[35m    >>> argon2.verify("wrong", h)[0m

[30;1m297 | [0m[35m    :returns:[0m

[30;1m61 | [0m[35mMost applications will only need to use two methods:[0m
[30;1m62 | [0m[35m:meth:`PasswordHash.hash` to generate new hashes, and :meth:`PasswordHash.verify`[0m
[30;1m63 | [0m[35mto check passwords against existing hashes.[0m

[30;1m60 | [0m[35m==============================[0m
[30;1m61 | [0m[35mMost applications will only need to use two methods:[0m
[30;1m62 | [0m[35m:meth:`PasswordHash.hash` to generate new hashes, and :meth:`PasswordHash.verify`[0m
[30;1m63 | [0m[35mto check passwords against existing hashes.[0m
[30;1m64 | [0m[35mThese methods provide an easy interface for working with a password hash,[0m

[30;1m435 | [0m[35m    * **[major]** Passing explicit configuration options to the :meth:`!PasswordHash.encrypt` method[0m
[30;1m436 | [0m[35m      (now called :meth:`PasswordHash.hash`) is deprecated.[0m
[30;1m437 | [0m[35m      To provide settings such as ``rounds`` and ``salt_size``, callers[0m
[30;1m438 | [0m[35m      should use the new :meth:`PasswordHash.using`[0m
[30;1m439 | [0m[35m      method, which generates a new hasher with a customized configuration.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m528[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m139 | [0m[35m  to upper case. While ASCII characters are uppercased as normal,[0m

[30;1m141 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m529[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m139 | [0m[35m  to upper case. While ASCII characters are uppercased as normal,[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m530[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m125 | [0m[35m  first encode the passwords into bytes, or override the default encoding[0m
[30;1m126 | [0m[35m  via ``lmhash.hash(secret, encoding="some-other-codec")``[0m
[30;1m127 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m128 | [0m[35m  All known encodings are ``us-ascii``-compatible, so for ASCII passwords,[0m
[30;1m129 | [0m[35m  the default should be sufficient.[0m
[30;1m130 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m131 | [0m[35m* Upper Case Conversion:[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m531[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.lmhash.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m122 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m123 | [0m[35m  Passlib uses ``cp437`` as it's default encoding for unicode strings.[0m
[30;1m124 | [0m[35m  However, if your database used a different encoding, you will need to either[0m
[30;1m125 | [0m[35m  first encode the passwords into bytes, or override the default encoding[0m
[30;1m126 | [0m[35m  via ``lmhash.hash(secret, encoding="some-other-codec")``[0m
[30;1m127 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m128 | [0m[35m  All known encodings are ``us-ascii``-compatible, so for ASCII passwords,[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m532[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.lmhash.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m117 | [0m[35m  non-ASCII characters to hash in a manner incompatible with the canonical[0m
[30;1m118 | [0m[35m  MS Windows implementation.[0m
[30;1m119 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m120 | [0m[35m  Thus if an application wishes to provide support for non-ASCII passwords,[0m
[30;1m121 | [0m[35m  it must decide which encoding to use.[0m
[30;1m122 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m123 | [0m[35m  Passlib uses ``cp437`` as it's default encoding for unicode strings.[0m

[30;1m47 | [0m[35mas possible, the meaning of "correct" is dependant on the software you are[0m

[30;1m45 | [0m[35missues, no two LMhash implementations handle non-``ascii`` characters in quite[0m
[30;1m46 | [0m[35mthe same way. While Passlib makes every attempt to behave as close to correct[0m

   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m

  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.lmhash.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m11 | [0m[35m.. currentmodule:: passlib.hash[0m
[30;1m12 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35mThis class implements the LanManager Hash (aka *LanMan* or *LM* hash).[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35mIt was used by early versions of Microsoft Windows to store user passwords,[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35muntil it was supplanted (though not entirely replaced) by[0m
[30;1m16 | [0m[35mthe :doc:`nthash <passlib.hash.nthash>` algorithm in Windows NT.[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35mIt continues to crop up in production due to its integral role[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m559[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.msdcc.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m63 | [0m[35m1. The password is encoded using ``UTF-16-LE``.[0m
[30;1m64 | [0m[35m2. The MD4 digest of step 1 is calculated.[0m
[30;1m65 | [0m[35m   (The result of this step is identical to the :class:`~passlib.hash.nthash`[0m
[30;1m66 | [0m[35m   of the password).[0m
[30;1m67 | [0m[35m3. The unicode username is converted to lowercase,[0m
[30;1m68 | [0m[35m   and encoded using ``UTF-16-LE``.[0m
[30;1m69 | [0m[35m   This should be just the plain username (e.g. ``User``[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m560[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.msdcc.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m60 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m61 | [0m[35mThe digest is calculated as follows:[0m
[30;1m62 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m63 | [0m[35m1. The password is encoded using ``UTF-16-LE``.[0m
[30;1m64 | [0m[35m2. The MD4 digest of step 1 is calculated.[0m
[30;1m65 | [0m[35m   (The result of this step is identical to the :class:`~passlib.hash.nthash`[0m
[30;1m66 | [0m[35m   of the password).[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m561[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m55 | [0m[35m==================[0m
[30;1m56 | [0m[35mMuch like :class:`!lmhash` and :class:`!nthash`, MS DCC hashes[0m
[30;1m57 | [0m[35mconsists of a 16 byte digest, usually encoded as 32 hexadecimal characters.[0m

[30;1m59 | [0m[35m``25fd08fa89795ed54207e6e8442a6ca0``.[0m
[30;1m60 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m61 | [0m[35mThe digest is calculated as follows:[0m

[30;1m286 | [0m[35mChoosing the right rounds value[0m
[30;1m287 | [0m[35m===============================[0m
[30;1m288 | [0m[35mFor hash algorithms with a variable time-cost,[0m
[30;1m289 | [0m[35mPasslib's :attr:`PasswordHash.default_rounds` values attempt to be secure enough for[0m
[30;1m290 | [0m[35mthe average [#avgsys]_ system. But the "right" value for a given hash[0m
[30;1m291 | [0m[35mis dependant on the server, its cpu, its expected load, and its users.[0m
[30;1m292 | [0m[35mSince larger values mean increased work for an attacker...[0m

[30;1m160 | [0m[35m=====================[0m
[30;1m161 | [0m[35mWithin its unittests, Passlib provides the :class:`~passlib.tests.utils.HandlerCase` class,[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m626[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m

[30;1m90 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m91 | [0m[35m    * provide an implementation of the :meth:`_calc_checksum` instance method.[0m
[30;1m92 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m93 | [0m[35m      this is the heart of the hash; this method should take in the password[0m
[30;1m94 | [0m[35m      as the first argument, then generate and return the digest portion[0m
[30;1m95 | [0m[35m      of the hash, according to the settings (such as salt, etc) stored[0m
[30;1m96 | [0m[35m      in the parsed instance this method was called from.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m627[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m72 | [0m[35mIn order to use :class:`!GenericHandler`, just subclass it, and then do the following:[0m
[30;1m73 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m74 | [0m[35m    * fill out the :attr:`name` attribute with the name of your hash.[0m
[30;1m75 | [0m[35m    * fill out the :attr:`~PasswordHash.setting_kwds` attribute with a tuple listing[0m
[30;1m76 | [0m[35m      all the settings your hash accepts.[0m
[30;1m77 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m78 | [0m[35m    * provide an implementation of the :meth:`from_string` classmethod.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m628[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m

[30;1m60 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m61 | [0m[35mWith this in mind, :class:`!GenericHandler` provides implementations[0m
[30;1m62 | [0m[35mof most of the :ref:`password-hash-api` methods, eliminating the need[0m
[30;1m63 | [0m[35mfor almost all the boilerplate associated with writing a password hash.[0m
[30;1m64 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m65 | [0m[35mIn order to minimize the amount of unneeded features that must be loaded in, the :class:`!GenericHan[0m
[30;1m66 | [0m[35mclass itself contains only the parts which are needed by almost all handlers: parsing, rendering, an[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m629[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.utils.handlers.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m59 | [0m[35m4. assemble hash, including new checksum, into a new string - performed by :meth:`~GenericHandler.to[0m
[30;1m60 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m61 | [0m[35mWith this in mind, :class:`!GenericHandler` provides implementations[0m
[30;1m62 | [0m[35mof most of the :ref:`password-hash-api` methods, eliminating the need[0m
[30;1m63 | [0m[35mfor almost all the boilerplate associated with writing a password hash.[0m
[30;1m64 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m65 | [0m[35mIn order to minimize the amount of unneeded features that must be loaded in, the :class:`!GenericHan[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m630[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m

[30;1m55 | [0m[35m2. validate constituent parts - performed by :class:`!GenericHandler`'s constructor,[0m
[30;1m56 | [0m[35m   and the normalization functions such as :meth:`~GenericHandler._norm_checksum` and :meth:`~HasSal[0m
[30;1m57 | [0m[35m   which are provided by its related mixin classes.[0m

[30;1m60 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m631[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m

[30;1m32 | [0m[35mThat said, most of the handlers built into Passlib are based around the :class:`GenericHandler`[0m
[30;1m33 | [0m[35mclass, and its associated mixin classes. While deriving from this class is not required,[0m
[30;1m34 | [0m[35mdoing so will greatly reduce the amount of additional code that is needed for[0m
[30;1m35 | [0m[35mall but the most convoluted password hash schemes.[0m
[30;1m36 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m25 | [0m[35m============================[0m

[30;1m1143 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m727[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/passlib/totp.py[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m398 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m399 | [0m[35m        CTR mode was chosen over CBC because the main attack scenario here[0m
[30;1m400 | [0m[35m        is that the attacker has stolen the database, and is trying to decrypt a TOTP key[0m
[30;1m401 | [0m[35m        (the plaintext value here).  To make it hard for them, we want every password[0m
[30;1m402 | [0m[35m        to decrypt to a potentially valid key -- thus need to avoid any authentication[0m
[30;1m403 | [0m[35m        or padding oracle attacks.  While some random padding construction could be devised[0m
[30;1m404 | [0m[35m        to make this work for CBC mode, a stream cipher mode is just plain simpler.[0m

[30;1m10 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m11 | [0m[35mThis class implements the md5-based hash algorithm used by PostgreSQL to store[0m
[30;1m12 | [0m[35mits user account passwords. This scheme was introduced in PostgreSQL 7.2;[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35mprior to this PostgreSQL stored its password in plain text.[0m

[30;1m123 | [0m[35mmaking it hard to fine-tune the amount of time taken to verify passwords;[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m837[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/history/1.5.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m20 | [0m[35m        (<= 1.5.2) generated salts in a manner which frequently set some of the[0m
[30;1m21 | [0m[35m        padding bits to 1.  While Passlib ignores these bits, many BCrypt[0m
[30;1m22 | [0m[35m        implementations perform password verification in a way which rejects[0m
[30;1m23 | [0m[35m        *all* passwords if any of the padding bits are set.  Thus Passlib's[0m
[30;1m24 | [0m[35m        BCrypt salt generation needed to be fixed to ensure compatibility,[0m
[30;1m25 | [0m[35m        and a route provided to correct existing hashes already out in the wild[0m
[30;1m26 | [0m[35m        :issue:`25`.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m838[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m19 | [0m[35m        BCrypt hashes contain 4 "padding" bits in the encoded salt, and Passlib[0m
[30;1m20 | [0m[35m        (<= 1.5.2) generated salts in a manner which frequently set some of the[0m

[30;1m19 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m111 | [0m[35m    except (OSError, subprocess.CalledProcessError):[0m
[30;1m112 | [0m[35m        # fallback - just use build date[0m
[30;1m113 | [0m[35m        now = int(os.environ.get('SOURCE_DATE_EPOCH') or time.time())[0m
[30;1m114 | [0m[35m        build_date = datetime.datetime.utcfromtimestamp(now)[0m
[30;1m115 | [0m[35m        stamp = build_date.strftime("%Y%m%d%H%M%S")[0m
[30;1m116 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m84 | [0m[35m    #: Many hashers default to False for historical / compatibility purposes,[0m
[30;1m85 | [0m[35m    #: indicating they will match on the truncated portion instead.[0m
[30;1m86 | [0m[35m    #: .. versionadded:: 1.7.1[0m

[30;1m124 | [0m[35m  as they may reveal the hash used one of the weak DES keys [#weak]_.[0m
[30;1m125 | [0m[35m  This information could theoretically allow an attacker to perform a[0m
[30;1m126 | [0m[35m  brute-force attack on a reduced keyspace and against only 1-2 rounds of DES.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1039[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m84 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m54 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m55 | [0m[35mThe Oracle 11 hash has a very simple algorithm: The salt is decoded[0m
[30;1m56 | [0m[35mfrom its hexadecimal representation into binary, and the SHA-1 digest[0m
[30;1m57 | [0m[35mof :samp:`{password}{raw_salt}` is then encoded into hexadecimal, and returned as the checksum.[0m
[30;1m58 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m59 | [0m[35mDeviations[0m
[30;1m60 | [0m[35m==========[0m

[30;1m42 | [0m[35mand :samp:`{checksum}` is the resulting 64-byte derived key, also[0m
[30;1m43 | [0m[35mencoded in upper-case hexadecimal. It can be identified by the prefix ``grub.pdkdf2.sha512.``.[0m
[30;1m44 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m45 | [0m[35mThe algorithm used is the same as :class:`pbkdf2_sha1`: the password is encoded into UTF-8 if not al[0m
[30;1m46 | [0m[35mand passed through :func:`~passlib.crypto.digest.pbkdf1`[0m
[30;1m47 | [0m[35malong with the decoded salt, and the number of rounds.[0m
[30;1m48 | [0m[35mThe result is then encoded into hexadecimal.[0m

   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m

   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m167 | [0m[35m  The underlying scheme implicitly allows rounds to have zero padding (e.g. ``$md5,rounds=001$abc$``[0m
[30;1m168 | [0m[35m  and also allows 0 rounds to be specified two ways (``$md5$abc$`` and ``$md5,rounds=0$abc$``).[0m
[30;1m169 | [0m[35m  Allowing either of these would result in multiple possible checksums[0m
[30;1m170 | [0m[35m  for the same password & salt. To prevent ambiguity,[0m
[30;1m171 | [0m[35m  Passlib will throw a :exc:`ValueError` if the rounds value is zero-padded,[0m
[30;1m172 | [0m[35m  or specified explicitly as 0 (e.g. ``$md5,rounds=0$abc$``).[0m
[30;1m173 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m159 | [0m[35m  In order to provide support for unicode strings,[0m
[30;1m160 | [0m[35m  Passlib will encode unicode passwords using ``utf-8``[0m
[30;1m161 | [0m[35m  before running them through sun-md5-crypt. If a different[0m
[30;1m162 | [0m[35m  encoding is desired by an application, the password should be encoded[0m
[30;1m163 | [0m[35m  before handing it to Passlib.[0m

[30;1m54 | [0m[35m=========[0m

  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.bcrypt_sha256.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m64 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m65 | [0m[35m* first the password is encoded to ``UTF-8`` if not already encoded.[0m
[30;1m66 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m67 | [0m[35m* the next step is to hash the password before handing it off to bcrypt:[0m
[30;1m68 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m69 | [0m[35m    - Under version 2 of this algorithm (the default as of  passlib 1.7.3), the password is run[0m
[30;1m70 | [0m[35m      through HMAC-SHA2-256, with the HMAC key set to the bcrypt salt (encoded as a 22 character asc[0m

[30;1m62 | [0m[35m=========[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1299[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m44 | [0m[35m======[0m
[30;1m45 | [0m[35mBcrypt-SHA256 is compatible with the :ref:`modular-crypt-format`, and uses ``$bcrypt-sha256$`` as th[0m
[30;1m46 | [0m[35mfor all it's strings.[0m
[30;1m47 | [0m[35mAn example hash (of ``password``) is:[0m
[30;1m48 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m49 | [0m[35m  ``$bcrypt-sha256$v=2,t=2b,r=12$n79VH.0Q2TMWmt3Oqt9uku$Kq4Noyk3094Y2QlB8NdRT8SvGiI4ft2``[0m
[30;1m50 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m225 | [0m[35m        Starting with this release, providing invalid values to[0m
[30;1m226 | [0m[35m        :meth:`PasswordHash.encrypt <passlib.ifc.PasswordHash.encrypt>`[0m
[30;1m227 | [0m[35m        will result in a :exc:`ValueError`. However, most hashes now accept[0m
[30;1m228 | [0m[35m        an optional ``relaxed=True`` keyword, which causes Passlib[0m
[30;1m229 | [0m[35m        to try and correct invalid values, and if successful,[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1317[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/history/1.6.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m208 | [0m[35m        This change is motivated a well-known `hmac timing attack <http://rdist.root.org/2009/05/28/[0m
[30;1m209 | [0m[35m        which exploits short-circuit string comparisons.[0m
[30;1m210 | [0m[35m        While this attack is not currently feasible against[0m
[30;1m211 | [0m[35m        most password hashes, some of the weaker unsalted[0m
[30;1m212 | [0m[35m        hashes supported by Passlib may be vulnerable; and this[0m
[30;1m213 | [0m[35m        change has been made preventatively to all of them.[0m
[30;1m214 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m131 | [0m[35m  In order to provide support for unicode strings,[0m
[30;1m132 | [0m[35m  Passlib will encode unicode passwords using ``utf-8``[0m
[30;1m133 | [0m[35m  before running them through sha256-crypt. If a different[0m
[30;1m134 | [0m[35m  encoding is desired by an application, the password should be encoded[0m
[30;1m135 | [0m[35m  before handing it to Passlib.[0m
[30;1m136 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m137 | [0m[35m.. rubric:: Footnotes[0m

[30;1m124 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m125 | [0m[35m  The underlying algorithm takes in a password specified[0m
[30;1m126 | [0m[35m  as a series of non-null bytes, and does not specify what encoding[0m
[30;1m127 | [0m[35m  should be used; though a ``us-ascii`` compatible encoding[0m
[30;1m128 | [0m[35m  is implied by nearly all implementations of sha256-crypt[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1425[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m161 | [0m[35m  and 2 padding bits. Because of the way they are coded, many BCrypt implementations[0m

[30;1m164 | [0m[35m  Passlib will print a warning if it encounters hashes with any padding bits set,[0m
[30;1m165 | [0m[35m  and then validate the hash as if the padding bits were cleared.[0m

   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m148 | [0m[35m  as well as all known reference hashes.[0m
[30;1m149 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m150 | [0m[35m  In order to provide support for unicode strings,[0m
[30;1m151 | [0m[35m  Passlib will encode unicode passwords using ``utf-8``[0m
[30;1m152 | [0m[35m  before running them through bcrypt. If a different[0m
[30;1m153 | [0m[35m  encoding is desired by an application, the password should be encoded[0m
[30;1m154 | [0m[35m  before handing it to Passlib.[0m

[30;1m8 | [0m[35mIt uses a modified version of the Blowfish stream cipher. Featuring[0m
[30;1m9 | [0m[35ma large salt and variable number of rounds, it's currently the default[0m

[30;1m12 | [0m[35mfor new applications. This class can be used directly as follows::[0m

[30;1m26 | [0m[35mThe :class:`!HTpasswdFile` class allows managing of htpasswd files.[0m
[30;1m27 | [0m[35mA quick summary of its usage::[0m
[30;1m28 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m29 | [0m[35m    >>> from passlib.apache import HtpasswdFile[0m
[30;1m30 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m31 | [0m[35m    >>> # when creating a new file, set to new=True, add entries, and save.[0m
[30;1m32 | [0m[35m    >>> ht = HtpasswdFile("test.htpasswd", new=True)[0m

[30;1m16 | [0m[35mThis class implements the "Type 7" password encoding used Cisco IOS.[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35mThis is not actually a true hash, but a reversible XOR Cipher encoding the plaintext[0m
[30;1m18 | [0m[35mpassword. Type 7 strings are (and were designed to be) plaintext equivalent;[0m
[30;1m19 | [0m[35mthe goal was to protect from "over the shoulder" eavesdropping, and[0m
[30;1m20 | [0m[35mlittle else. They can be trivially decoded.[0m
[30;1m21 | [0m[35mThis class can be used directly as follows::[0m

[30;1m14 | [0m[35m.. currentmodule:: passlib.hash[0m

[30;1m17 | [0m[35mThis is not actually a true hash, but a reversible XOR Cipher encoding the plaintext[0m

[30;1m188 | [0m[35m  In order to provide support for unicode strings,[0m
[30;1m189 | [0m[35m  Passlib will encode unicode passwords using ``utf-8``[0m
[30;1m190 | [0m[35m  before running them through md5-crypt. If a different[0m
[30;1m191 | [0m[35m  encoding is desired by an application, the password should be encoded[0m

[30;1m926 | [0m[35m        a new htpasswd file, applications can set ``new=True`` so that[0m

[30;1m929 | [0m[35m        .. versionadded:: 1.6[0m

[30;1m91 | [0m[35m  of the raw derived key bytes returned from the PBKDF2 function.[0m

[30;1m93 | [0m[35m  as the size of the raw derived key. This is enlarged[0m
[30;1m94 | [0m[35m  by approximately 4/3 by the base64 encoding,[0m

[30;1m87 | [0m[35m* :samp:`{salt}` - this is the :func:`adapted base64 encoding <passlib.utils.binary.ab64_encode>`[0m
[30;1m88 | [0m[35m  of the raw salt bytes passed into the PBKDF2 function.[0m
[30;1m89 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m90 | [0m[35m* :samp:`{checksum}` - this is the :func:`adapted base64 encoding <passlib.utils.binary.ab64_encode>[0m
[30;1m91 | [0m[35m  of the raw derived key bytes returned from the PBKDF2 function.[0m
[30;1m92 | [0m[35m  Each scheme uses the digest size of its specific hash algorithm (:samp:`{digest}`)[0m
[30;1m93 | [0m[35m  as the size of the raw derived key. This is enlarged[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1798[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m84 | [0m[35m  this is encoded as a positive decimal number with no zero-padding[0m

[30;1m86 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m89 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1799[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m95 | [0m[35m  resulting in a checksum size of 27, 43, and 86 for each of the respective algorithms listed above.[0m
[30;1m96 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m97 | [0m[35mThe algorithm used by all of these schemes is deliberately identical and simple:[0m
[30;1m98 | [0m[35mThe password is encoded into UTF-8 if not already encoded,[0m
[30;1m99 | [0m[35mand run through :func:`~passlib.crypto.digest.pbkdf2_hmac`[0m

   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.ldap_crypt.rst[0m

[30;1m8 | [0m[35mLDAP hash formats specified by :rfc:`2307`.[0m
[30;1m9 | [0m[35mOne of these, identified by RFC 2307 as the ``{CRYPT}`` scheme,[0m
[30;1m10 | [0m[35mis somewhat different from the others.[0m
[30;1m11 | [0m[35mInstead of specifying a password hashing scheme,[0m
[30;1m12 | [0m[35mit's supposed to wrap the host OS's :func:`!crypt()`.[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35mBeing host-dependant, the actual hashes supported[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35mby this scheme may differ greatly between host systems.[0m

[30;1m51 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m22 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m23 | [0m[35mSince this format is PBKDF2-based, it has equivalent security to[0m

[30;1m25 | [0m[35mand can be used to authenticate users using either the normal :ref:`password-hash-api`[0m

[30;1m28 | [0m[35m.. note::[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1843[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m

[30;1m15 | [0m[35mSCRAM.[0m
[30;1m16 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35mTo accomplish this, Passlib provides the following[0m
[30;1m18 | [0m[35m:ref:`modular-crypt-format`-compatible password hash scheme which uses the[0m
[30;1m19 | [0m[35m``$scram$`` identifier. This format encodes a salt, rounds settings, and one[0m
[30;1m20 | [0m[35mor more :func:`~passlib.crypto.digest.pbkdf2_hmac` digests... one digest for each[0m
[30;1m21 | [0m[35mof the hash algorithms the server wishes to support over SCRAM.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1844[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m11 | [0m[35mSCRAM is a password-based challenge response protocol defined by :rfc:`5802`.[0m

[30;1m15 | [0m[35mSCRAM.[0m

[30;1m17 | [0m[35mTo accomplish this, Passlib provides the following[0m

[30;1m285 | [0m[35mclass msdcc2(uh.HasUserContext, uh.StaticHandler):[0m
[30;1m286 | [0m[35m    """This class implements version 2 of Microsoft's Domain Cached Credentials[0m
[30;1m287 | [0m[35m    password hash, and follows the :ref:`password-hash-api`.[0m
[30;1m288 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m289 | [0m[35m    It has a fixed number of rounds, and uses the associated[0m
[30;1m290 | [0m[35m    username as the salt.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1853[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/passlib/handlers/windows.py[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m268 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m269 | [0m[35m    @classmethod[0m
[30;1m270 | [0m[35m    def raw(cls, secret, user):[0m
[30;1m271 | [0m[35m        """encode password using mscash v1 algorithm[0m
[30;1m272 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m110 | [0m[35m  In order to provide support for unicode strings,[0m
[30;1m111 | [0m[35m  Passlib will encode unicode passwords using ``utf-8``[0m
[30;1m112 | [0m[35m  before running them through crypt16. If a different[0m

[30;1m105 | [0m[35m* Unicode Policy:[0m
[30;1m106 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1934[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.crypt16.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m92 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m93 | [0m[35m* For a given salt, passwords under 9 characters all have the same 2nd checksum.[0m

[30;1m98 | [0m[35m  (by doing 5 rounds, checking the result against checksum 2,[0m

[30;1m89 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m90 | [0m[35m* Max Password Size[0m
[30;1m91 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m92 | [0m[35m  Windows appears to enforce a maximum password size,[0m
[30;1m93 | [0m[35m  but the actual value of this limit is unclear; sources[0m
[30;1m94 | [0m[35m  report it to be set at assorted values from 26 to 128 characters,[0m
[30;1m95 | [0m[35m  and it may in fact vary between Windows releases. [0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1951[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.msdcc2.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m87 | [0m[35mDeviations[0m
[30;1m88 | [0m[35m==========[0m
[30;1m89 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m90 | [0m[35m* Max Password Size[0m
[30;1m91 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m92 | [0m[35m  Windows appears to enforce a maximum password size,[0m
[30;1m93 | [0m[35m  but the actual value of this limit is unclear; sources[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1952[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.msdcc2.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m79 | [0m[35m===============[0m
[30;1m80 | [0m[35mThis hash is essentially :doc:`msdcc v1 <passlib.hash.msdcc>` with a fixed-round PBKDF2 function[0m
[30;1m81 | [0m[35mwrapped around it. The number of rounds of PBKDF2 is currently[0m
[30;1m82 | [0m[35msufficient to make this a semi-reasonable way to store passwords,[0m
[30;1m83 | [0m[35mbut the use of the lowercase username as a salt, and the fact[0m
[30;1m84 | [0m[35mthat the rounds can't be increased, means this hash is not particularly[0m
[30;1m85 | [0m[35mfuture-proof, and should not be used for new applications.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1953[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.msdcc2.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m60 | [0m[35m1. The password is encoded using ``UTF-16-LE``.[0m
[30;1m61 | [0m[35m2. The MD4 digest of step 1 is calculated.[0m
[30;1m62 | [0m[35m   (The result of this is identical to the :class:`~passlib.hash.nthash`[0m
[30;1m63 | [0m[35m   digest of the password).[0m
[30;1m64 | [0m[35m3. The unicode username is converted to lowercase,[0m
[30;1m65 | [0m[35m   and encoded using ``UTF-16-LE``.[0m
[30;1m66 | [0m[35m   This should be just the plain username (e.g. ``User``[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1954[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.msdcc2.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m57 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m58 | [0m[35mThe digest is calculated as follows:[0m
[30;1m59 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m60 | [0m[35m1. The password is encoded using ``UTF-16-LE``.[0m
[30;1m61 | [0m[35m2. The MD4 digest of step 1 is calculated.[0m
[30;1m62 | [0m[35m   (The result of this is identical to the :class:`~passlib.hash.nthash`[0m
[30;1m63 | [0m[35m   digest of the password).[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1955[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.msdcc2.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m52 | [0m[35m==================[0m
[30;1m53 | [0m[35mMuch like :class:`!lmhash`, :class:`!nthash`, and :class:`!msdcc`,[0m
[30;1m54 | [0m[35mMS DCC v2 hashes consists of a 16 byte digest, usually encoded as 32[0m

[30;1m56 | [0m[35maccount ``"Administrator"``) is ``4c253e4b65c007a8cd683ea57bc43c76``.[0m
[30;1m57 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m58 | [0m[35mThe digest is calculated as follows:[0m

[30;1m147 | [0m[35m            where *digest* matches the raw bytes returned by[0m

[30;1m258 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m260 | [0m[35m    will result in a :exc:`~passlib.exc.PasswordSizeError` if passed to :meth:`~cisco_asa.hash`,[0m
[30;1m261 | [0m[35m    and be silently rejected if passed to :meth:`~cisco_asa.verify`.[0m
[30;1m262 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2165[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m

[30;1m8 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m9 | [0m[35mThis class provides an implementation of Cryptacular's[0m
[30;1m10 | [0m[35mPBKDF2-HMAC-SHA1 hash format [#cta]_. PBKDF2 is a key derivation function [#pbkdf2]_[0m
[30;1m11 | [0m[35mthat is ideally suited as the basis for a password hash, as it provides[0m
[30;1m12 | [0m[35mvariable length salts, variable number of rounds.[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35m.. seealso::[0m

[30;1m20 | [0m[35mNote that these functions do not support multi-block operation or decryption,[0m

[30;1m9 | [0m[35m.. currentmodule:: passlib.hash[0m
[30;1m10 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m11 | [0m[35mThis class implements the hash algorithm used by Microsoft SQL Server 2005[0m
[30;1m12 | [0m[35mto store its user account passwords, replacing the slightly less secure[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35m:class:`~passlib.hash.mssql2000` variant.[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35mThis class can be used directly as follows::[0m

[30;1m14 | [0m[35m========[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35m.. include:: ../_fragments/asa_verify_callout.rst[0m
[30;1m16 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35mThe :class:`cisco_asa` class implements the "encrypted" password hash algorithm commonly found on Ci[0m
[30;1m18 | [0m[35mASA systems. The companion :class:`cisco_pix` class[0m
[30;1m19 | [0m[35mimplements the older variant found on Cisco PIX.[0m
[30;1m20 | [0m[35mAside from internal differences, and slightly different limitations,[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2298[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/passlib/crypto/_md4.py[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m3 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m4 | [0m[35mHelper implementing insecure and obsolete md4 algorithm.[0m
[30;1m5 | [0m[35mused for NTHASH format, which is also insecure and broken,[0m
[30;1m6 | [0m[35msince it's just md4(password).[0m
[30;1m7 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m8 | [0m[35mImplementated based on rfc at http://www.faqs.org/rfcs/rfc1320.html[0m
[30;1m9 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2299[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m62 | [0m[35m         `<http://djangosnippets.org/snippets/1508/>`_[0m

[30;1m64 | [0m[35m.. [#f2] Mysql document describing transition -[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2300[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.mysql323.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m54 | [0m[35mLacking any sort of salt, ignoring all whitespace,[0m
[30;1m55 | [0m[35mand having a simplistic algorithm that amounts to little more than a checksum,[0m
[30;1m56 | [0m[35mthis is not secure, and should not be used for *any* purpose[0m
[30;1m57 | [0m[35mbut verifying existing MySQL 3.2.3 - 4.0 password hashes.[0m
[30;1m58 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m59 | [0m[35m.. rubric:: Footnotes[0m
[30;1m60 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2301[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.mysql323.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m41 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m42 | [0m[35mFormat & Algorithm[0m
[30;1m43 | [0m[35m==================[0m
[30;1m44 | [0m[35mA mysql-323 password hash consists of 16 hexadecimal digits,[0m
[30;1m45 | [0m[35mdirectly encoding the 64 bit checksum. MySQL always uses[0m
[30;1m46 | [0m[35mlower-case letters, and so does Passlib[0m
[30;1m47 | [0m[35m(though Passlib will recognize upper case letters as well).[0m

[30;1m97 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m98 | [0m[35m    Because of the chained structure, bigcrypt has the property that[0m
[30;1m99 | [0m[35m    the first 13 characters of any bigcrypt hash form a valid :class:`~passlib.hash.des_crypt`[0m
[30;1m100 | [0m[35m    hash of the same password; and bigcrypt hashes of any passwords[0m
[30;1m101 | [0m[35m    less than 9 characters will be identical to des-crypt.[0m
[30;1m102 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m103 | [0m[35mSecurity Issues[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2324[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.bigcrypt.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m97 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m98 | [0m[35m    Because of the chained structure, bigcrypt has the property that[0m

[30;1m86 | [0m[35m   an additional checksum is generated by repeating steps 3..7,[0m
[30;1m87 | [0m[35m   with the following changes:[0m
[30;1m88 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m89 | [0m[35m   a. Step 3 uses the specified 8 bytes of the password, instead of the first 8 bytes.[0m
[30;1m90 | [0m[35m   b. Step 4 uses the first two characters from the previous checksum[0m
[30;1m91 | [0m[35m      as the salt for the next checksum.[0m
[30;1m92 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2326[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m82 | [0m[35m   using the :data:`hash64-big <passlib.utils.binary.h64big>` format.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2327[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m

[30;1m53 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m54 | [0m[35mIn order to generate the checksum, the password is first encoded into UTF-8 if it's unicode.[0m
[30;1m55 | [0m[35mThen, the entire configuration string (all of the hash except the checksum, ie :samp:`$p5k2${rounds}[0m
[30;1m56 | [0m[35mis used as the PBKDF2 salt. PBKDF2 is called using the encoded password, the full salt,[0m
[30;1m57 | [0m[35mthe specified number of rounds, and using HMAC-SHA1 as its pseudorandom function.[0m
[30;1m58 | [0m[35m24 bytes of derived key are requested, and the resulting key is encoded and used[0m
[30;1m59 | [0m[35mas the checksum portion of the hash.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2349[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m52 | [0m[35m  (``b8TQ5AMQemtlaSgegw5Je.JBE3QQhLbO`` in the example).[0m

[30;1m50 | [0m[35mto enable administrators to store user passwords in a manner compatible with[0m

[30;1m47 | [0m[35m===============[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2396[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m37 | [0m[35mFormat & Algorithm[0m
[30;1m38 | [0m[35m==================[0m
[30;1m39 | [0m[35mA nthash consists of 32 hexadecimal digits, which encode the digest.[0m
[30;1m40 | [0m[35mAn example hash (of ``password``) is ``8846f7eaee8fb117ad06bdd830b7586c``.[0m
[30;1m41 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m42 | [0m[35mThe digest is calculated by encoding the secret using ``UTF-16-LE``,[0m
[30;1m43 | [0m[35mtaking the MD4 digest, and then encoding[0m

[30;1m127 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m128 | [0m[35m   Most modular crypt format hashes follow this convention,[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2422[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/modular_crypt_format.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m116 | [0m[35m   at the end of the hash, preferably separated[0m
[30;1m117 | [0m[35m   by a ``$``.[0m
[30;1m118 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m119 | [0m[35m   This allows password hashes to be easily truncated[0m
[30;1m120 | [0m[35m   to a "configuration string" containing just[0m
[30;1m121 | [0m[35m   the identifying prefix, rounds, salt, etc.[0m
[30;1m122 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2423[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/modular_crypt_format.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m101 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m102 | [0m[35m   The only hard and fast stricture[0m
[30;1m103 | [0m[35m   is that ``:;!*`` and all non-printable or 8-bit characters be avoided,[0m
[30;1m104 | [0m[35m   since this would interfere with parsing of the Unix shadow password file,[0m
[30;1m105 | [0m[35m   where these hashes are typically stored.[0m
[30;1m106 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m107 | [0m[35m   Pretty much all older modular-crypt-format hashes[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2424[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/modular_crypt_format.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m32 | [0m[35mThis page is an attempt to document what that means.[0m
[30;1m33 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m34 | [0m[35mIn short, the modular crypt format (MCF) is a standard[0m
[30;1m35 | [0m[35mfor encoding password hash strings, which requires hashes[0m
[30;1m36 | [0m[35mhave the format :samp:`${identifier}${content}`; where[0m
[30;1m37 | [0m[35m:samp:`{identifier}` is an short alphanumeric string uniquely[0m
[30;1m38 | [0m[35midentifying a particular scheme, and :samp:`{content}`[0m

[30;1m59 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m60 | [0m[35mTwo-Factor Authentication[0m
[30;1m61 | [0m[35m=========================[0m
[30;1m62 | [0m[35mWhile not strictly connected to password hashing, modern applications frequently[0m
[30;1m63 | [0m[35mneed to perform the related task of two-factor authentication.  One of the most[0m
[30;1m64 | [0m[35mcommon protocols for doing this is TOTP (:rfc:`6238`).[0m
[30;1m65 | [0m[35mTo help get TOTP in place, the :mod:`passlib.totp` module provides a set of helper functions[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2456[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/narr/overview.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m46 | [0m[35m:class:`!CryptContext`, which attempts to solve all of these problems[0m
[30;1m47 | [0m[35m(or at least relieve developers of most of the burden).[0m
[30;1m48 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m49 | [0m[35mThis class handles managing multiple password hash schemes,[0m
[30;1m50 | [0m[35mdeprecation & migration of old hashes, and supports a simple configuration[0m
[30;1m51 | [0m[35mlanguage that can be serialized to an INI file.[0m
[30;1m52 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2551[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m50 | [0m[35mPHPass uses a straightforward algorithm to calculate the checksum:[0m
[30;1m51 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m52 | [0m[35m1. an initial result is generated from the MD5 digest of the salt string + the secret.[0m
[30;1m53 | [0m[35m2. for :samp:`2**{rounds}` iterations, a new result is created from the MD5 digest of the last resul[0m
[30;1m54 | [0m[35m3. the last result is then encoded according to the format described above.[0m
[30;1m55 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m56 | [0m[35mDeviations[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2552[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m24 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m25 | [0m[35mFormat[0m
[30;1m26 | [0m[35m==================[0m
[30;1m27 | [0m[35mAn example hash (of ``password``) is ``$P$8ohUJ.1sdFw09/bMaAQPTGDNi2BIUt1``.[0m
[30;1m28 | [0m[35mA phpass portable hash string has the format :samp:`$P${rounds}{salt}{checksum}`, where:[0m
[30;1m29 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m30 | [0m[35m* ``$P$`` is the prefix used to identify phpass hashes,[0m

[30;1m9 | [0m[35mThis algorithm is used primarily by PHP software[0m
[30;1m10 | [0m[35mwhich uses PHPass [#pp]_,[0m
[30;1m11 | [0m[35ma PHP library similar to Passlib. The PHPass Portable Hash[0m
[30;1m12 | [0m[35mis a custom password hash used by PHPass as a fallback[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35mwhen none of its other hashes are available.[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35mDue to its reliance on MD5, and the simplistic implementation,[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35mother hash algorithms should be used if possible.[0m

[30;1m9 | [0m[35m.. currentmodule:: passlib.hash[0m
[30;1m10 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m11 | [0m[35mThis class implements the hash algorithm used by Microsoft SQL Server 2000[0m
[30;1m12 | [0m[35mto store its user account passwords, until it was replaced[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35mby a slightly more secure variant (:class:`~passlib.hash.mssql2005`)[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35min MSSQL 2005.[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35mThis class can be used directly as follows::[0m

[30;1m102 | [0m[35m==========[0m
[30;1m103 | [0m[35m* Unicode Policy:[0m
[30;1m104 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m106 | [0m[35m  as a series of bytes, and does not specify what encoding[0m
[30;1m107 | [0m[35m  should be used; though a ``us-ascii`` compatible encoding[0m
[30;1m108 | [0m[35m  is implied by the implementation,[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2593[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.fshp.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m85 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m86 | [0m[35mSecurity Issues[0m
[30;1m87 | [0m[35m===============[0m
[30;1m88 | [0m[35m* A minor issue is that FSHP swaps the location the password and salt[0m
[30;1m89 | [0m[35m  from what is described in the PBKDF1 standard.[0m
[30;1m90 | [0m[35m  This issue is mainly noted in order to dismiss it:[0m
[30;1m91 | [0m[35m  while the swap permits an attacker to pre-calculate part of the initial digest,[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2594[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m

[30;1m81 | [0m[35mpassing in the password, the decoded salt string, the number of[0m
[30;1m82 | [0m[35mrounds, and hash function specified by the variant identifier.[0m
[30;1m83 | [0m[35mFSHP has one quirk in that the password is passed in as the pbkdf1 salt,[0m
[30;1m84 | [0m[35mand the salt is passed in as the pbkdf1 password.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2596[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m

[30;1m78 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m79 | [0m[35mFSHP is basically just a wrapper around PBKDF1:[0m
[30;1m80 | [0m[35mThe checksum is calculated using :func:`~passlib.crypto.digest.pbkdf1`,[0m
[30;1m81 | [0m[35mpassing in the password, the decoded salt string, the number of[0m
[30;1m82 | [0m[35mrounds, and hash function specified by the variant identifier.[0m

[30;1m84 | [0m[35mand the salt is passed in as the pbkdf1 password.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2597[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m

   Pattern: [32m(npm owner|password|htpasswd|auth_?token|secret_?key|private_?key|authorized_keys?|npmrc|\.ssh|usersecrets?|api_?keys|nuget\.config|\.identityservice)[0m
[30;1m49 | [0m[35m==================[0m
[30;1m50 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m51 | [0m[35mthe password is encoded into UTF-8 if not already encoded.[0m
[30;1m52 | [0m[35mUsing the specified salt, and a fixed 10000 rounds,[0m
[30;1m53 | [0m[35mPBKDF2-HMAC-SHA1 is used to generate a 32 byte key,[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2611[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000800[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.Obfuscation[0m
  Severity: [36mImportant[0m, Confidence: [36mHigh[0m
  Filename: [33m/passlib-1.7.4/docs/lib/passlib.hash.atlassian_pbkdf2_sha1.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32mbase64|encodedcommand|obfuscate[0m
[30;1m31 | [0m[35m==================[0m
[30;1m32 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m33 | [0m[35mAll of this scheme's hashes have the format :samp:`\\{PKCS5S2\\}{data}`,[0m
[30;1m34 | [0m[35mwhere :samp:`{data}` is a 64 character base64 encoded string;[0m
[30;1m35 | [0m[35mwhich (when decoded), contains a 16 byte salt,[0m
[30;1m36 | [0m[35mand a 32 byte checksum.[0m
[30;1m37 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2612[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000701[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Token[0m

[30;1m48 | [0m[35m    ``edf96e6e3591f8d96b9ed4addc47a7632edea176bb2fa8a03fa3179b75b5bf09``[0m
[30;1m49 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m50 | [0m[35mWhen calculating the checksum:[0m
[30;1m51 | [0m[35mthe password is encoded into UTF-8 if not already encoded.[0m
[30;1m52 | [0m[35mUsing the specified salt, and a fixed 10000 rounds,[0m
[30;1m53 | [0m[35mPBKDF2-HMAC-SHA1 is used to generate a 32 byte key,[0m
[30;1m54 | [0m[35mwhich appended to the salt and encoded in base64.[0m

[30;1m50 | [0m[35mBasic Usage[0m
[30;1m51 | [0m[35m===========[0m
[30;1m52 | [0m[35mAt its base, the :class:`!CryptContext` class is just a collection of[0m
[30;1m53 | [0m[35m:class:`~passlib.ifc.PasswordHash` objects, imported by name[0m
[30;1m54 | [0m[35mfrom the :mod:`passlib.hash` module. The following snippet creates[0m
[30;1m55 | [0m[35ma new context object which supports three hash algorithms[0m

[30;1m13 | [0m[35mThe :mod:`passlib.context` module contains one main class: :class:`!passlib.context.CryptContext`.[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35mThis class is designed to take care of many of the more frequent[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35mcoding patterns which occur in applications that need to handle multiple[0m

[30;1m577 | [0m[35mGenerating Tokens (Client-Side Only)[0m
[30;1m578 | [0m[35m====================================[0m
[30;1m579 | [0m[35mFinally, the whole point of TOTP: generating and verifying tokens.[0m
[30;1m580 | [0m[35mThe TOTP protocol generates a new time & key -dependant token every <period> seconds (usually 30).[0m
[30;1m581 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m582 | [0m[35mGenerating a totp token is done with the :meth:`TOTP.generate` method,[0m
[30;1m583 | [0m[35mwhich returns a :class:`TotpToken` instance.  This object looks and acts[0m

[30;1m349 | [0m[35mall TOTP instances to have.  This includes application secrets (for encrypting[0m
[30;1m350 | [0m[35mTOTP keys for storage), or setting a default issuer label (for rendering URIs).[0m
[30;1m351 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m352 | [0m[35mInstead of having to call the :class:`TOTP` constructor each time and provide[0m

[30;1m354 | [0m[35mThis method takes in a number of the same options as the TOTP constructor,[0m
[30;1m355 | [0m[35mand returns a :class:`TOTP` subclass which has these options pre-programmed[0m

[30;1m653 | [0m[35m    to the amount of time taken can vary between hashes. This attribute[0m
[30;1m654 | [0m[35m    indicates the scale used by the hash:[0m
[30;1m655 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m656 | [0m[35m    * ``"linear"`` - time taken scales linearly with rounds value[0m

[30;1m79 | [0m[35mThis algorithm is should not be used for any purpose besides[0m
[30;1m80 | [0m[35mmanipulating existing DCC v1 hashes, due to the following flaws:[0m
[30;1m81 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m11 | [0m[35mThis class implements the md5-based hash algorithm used by PostgreSQL to store[0m
[30;1m12 | [0m[35mits user account passwords. This scheme was introduced in PostgreSQL 7.2;[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35mprior to this PostgreSQL stored its password in plain text.[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35mUsers will most likely find the frontend provided by :mod:`passlib.apps`[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35mto be more useful than accessing this class directly.[0m
[30;1m16 | [0m[35mThat aside, this class can be used directly as follows::[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m126 | [0m[35mthe first 72 characters of a password, and will silently truncate longer ones[0m

[30;1m39 | [0m[35m      have any such hashes automatically re-encoded the next time the user[0m
[30;1m40 | [0m[35m      logs in.[0m
[30;1m41 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m42 | [0m[35m    *To fix existing hashes:*[0m

[30;1m107 | [0m[35m===============[0m
[30;1m108 | [0m[35m`SCrypt <http://www.tarsnap.com/scrypt.html>`__ is the first in a class of "memory-hard"[0m
[30;1m109 | [0m[35mkey derivation functions. Initially, it looked very promising as a replacement for BCrypt,[0m
[30;1m110 | [0m[35mPBKDF2, and SHA512-Crypt.  However, the fact that it's ``N`` parameter controls both[0m
[30;1m111 | [0m[35mtime *and* memory cost means the two cannot be varied completely independantly.  This[0m
[30;1m112 | [0m[35meventually proved to be problematic, as ``N`` values required for even BCrypt levels of security[0m
[30;1m113 | [0m[35mresulting in memory requirements that were unacceptable on most production systems.[0m
[30;1m114 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m24 | [0m[35m  of the hash that's returned.[0m
[30;1m25 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m26 | [0m[35m  There are just a few hashes which require an external salt (like a username),[0m

[30;1m28 | [0m[35m  be used in unless you already know *why* you need to use them.[0m
[30;1m29 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m30 | [0m[35m* **How do I decrypt the hashes generated by Passlib?**[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m3155[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m

   Pattern: [32m\s(apt|apt\-get|aria2c|arp|ash|awk|base64|bash|bpftrace|busybox|cat|chmod|chown|cp|cpan|cpulimit|crontab|csh|curl|cut|dash|dd|diff|dmesg|dmsetup|dnf|docker|dpkg|easy_install|ed|emacs|env|expand|expect|facter|find|finger|flock|fmt|ftp|gawk|gdb|gimp|git|grep|head|iftop|ionice|ip|irb|jjs|journalctl|jrunscript|ksh|ld\.so|ldconfig|logsave|ltrace|lua|mail|mawk|mount|mtr|mv|mysql|nano|nawk|nc|nice|nl|nmap|node|od|openssl|perl|pg|php|pic|pico|pip|puppet|readelf|red|rlogin|rlwrap|rpm|rpmquery|rsync|ruby|run\-mailcap|run\-parts|rvim|scp|screen|script|sed|service|setarch|sftp|shuf|smbclient|socat|sort|sqlite3|ssh|start\-stop\-daemon|stdbuf|strace|systemctl|tail|tar|taskset|tclsh|tcpdump|tee|telnet|tftp|time|timeout|tmux|top|ul|unexpand|uniq|unshare|vi|vim|watch|wget|whois|wish|xargs|xxd|yum|zsh|zypper)\s[0m
[30;1m12 | [0m[35m  input generates a different result! What's going on?**[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35m  For all the hashes which include a salt, :meth:`PasswordHash.hash`[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35m  will automatically generate a new one each time it's invoked.[0m
[30;1m16 | [0m[35m  Thus the salt & digest portions of the resulting hash string will be[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35m  different every time.[0m
[30;1m18 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m3 | [0m[35m.. danger::[0m

[30;1m67 | [0m[35m    during digest comparisons: the standard ``==`` operator aborts[0m

[30;1m69 | [0m[35m    proportional to the longest prefix shared by the two inputs.[0m

[30;1m155 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m156 | [0m[35m* Padding Bits[0m
[30;1m157 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m158 | [0m[35m  BCrypt's base64 encoding results in the last character of the salt[0m
[30;1m159 | [0m[35m  encoding only 2 bits of data, the remaining 4 are "padding" bits.[0m
[30;1m160 | [0m[35m  Similarly, the last character of the digest contains 4 bits of data,[0m
[30;1m161 | [0m[35m  and 2 padding bits. Because of the way they are coded, many BCrypt implementations[0m

[30;1m41 | [0m[35mdef validate(n, r, p):[0m
[30;1m42 | [0m[35m    """[0m
[30;1m43 | [0m[35m    helper which validates a set of scrypt config parameters.[0m
[30;1m44 | [0m[35m    scrypt will take ``O(n * r * p)`` time and ``O(n * r)`` memory.[0m
[30;1m45 | [0m[35m    limitations are that ``n = 2**<positive integer>``, ``n < 2**(16*r)``, ``r * p < 2 ** 30``.[0m

[30;1m47 | [0m[35m    :param n: scrypt rounds[0m

[30;1m604 | [0m[35m##    # parity calc adapted from 32-bit even parity alg found at[0m

[30;1m830 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m832 | [0m[35m    # make sure block count won't overflow (per pbkdf2 spec)[0m
[30;1m833 | [0m[35m    # this corresponds to throwing error if keylen > digest_size * MAX_UINT32[0m
[30;1m834 | [0m[35m    # NOTE: stdlib will throw error at lower bound (keylen > MAX_SINT32)[0m

[30;1m42 | [0m[35mFormat & Algorithm[0m
[30;1m43 | [0m[35m==================[0m
[30;1m44 | [0m[35mA mysql-323 password hash consists of 16 hexadecimal digits,[0m
[30;1m45 | [0m[35mdirectly encoding the 64 bit checksum. MySQL always uses[0m
[30;1m46 | [0m[35mlower-case letters, and so does Passlib[0m
[30;1m47 | [0m[35m(though Passlib will recognize upper case letters as well).[0m
[30;1m48 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m125 | [0m[35m=======[0m
[30;1m126 | [0m[35mPasslib contains a comprehensive set of unittests (about 38% of the total code),[0m
[30;1m127 | [0m[35mwhich provide nearly complete coverage, and verification of the hash[0m
[30;1m128 | [0m[35malgorithms using multiple external sources (if detected at runtime).[0m
[30;1m129 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m130 | [0m[35mAll unit tests are contained within the :mod:`passlib.tests` subpackage,[0m
[30;1m131 | [0m[35mand are designed to be run using the[0m

   Pattern: [32m\s(apt|apt\-get|aria2c|arp|ash|awk|base64|bash|bpftrace|busybox|cat|chmod|chown|cp|cpan|cpulimit|crontab|csh|curl|cut|dash|dd|diff|dmesg|dmsetup|dnf|docker|dpkg|easy_install|ed|emacs|env|expand|expect|facter|find|finger|flock|fmt|ftp|gawk|gdb|gimp|git|grep|head|iftop|ionice|ip|irb|jjs|journalctl|jrunscript|ksh|ld\.so|ldconfig|logsave|ltrace|lua|mail|mawk|mount|mtr|mv|mysql|nano|nawk|nc|nice|nl|nmap|node|od|openssl|perl|pg|php|pic|pico|pip|puppet|readelf|red|rlogin|rlwrap|rpm|rpmquery|rsync|ruby|run\-mailcap|run\-parts|rvim|scp|screen|script|sed|service|setarch|sftp|shuf|smbclient|socat|sort|sqlite3|ssh|start\-stop\-daemon|stdbuf|strace|systemctl|tail|tar|taskset|tclsh|tcpdump|tee|telnet|tftp|time|timeout|tmux|top|ul|unexpand|uniq|unshare|vi|vim|watch|wget|whois|wish|xargs|xxd|yum|zsh|zypper)\s[0m
[30;1m106 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m107 | [0m[35m   Pretty much all older modular-crypt-format hashes[0m
[30;1m108 | [0m[35m   use ascii letters, numbers, ``.``, and ``/``[0m
[30;1m109 | [0m[35m   to provide base64 encoding of their raw data,[0m
[30;1m110 | [0m[35m   though the exact character value assignments vary between hashes[0m
[30;1m111 | [0m[35m   (see :data:`passlib.utils.h64`).[0m
[30;1m112 | [0m[35m   Many newer hashes use ``+`` instead of ``.``,[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m3569[0m[34m of [0m[33m3649[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m

[30;1m55 | [0m[35mmultiple hashes on one system, or progressively migrate to a newer scheme.[0m
[30;1m56 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m57 | [0m[35mThis was solved with the advent of the MCF,[0m
[30;1m58 | [0m[35mwhich was introduced around the time that :class:`~passlib.hash.md5_crypt` was developed.[0m
[30;1m59 | [0m[35mThis format allows hashes from multiple schemes to exist within the same[0m
[30;1m60 | [0m[35mdatabase, by requiring that all hash strings begin with a unique prefix[0m
[30;1m61 | [0m[35musing the format :samp:`${identifier}$`.[0m
